{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535945"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:01:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:01:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15560"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15560"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.3,0.24,0.12,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8251"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99898"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8251"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15560"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82290"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5781"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29722"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34299"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43581"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99898"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of left-sided lower back pain. The pain is worse with standing and walking, and improves with rest. He has no radiation of pain to the legs and no neurological symptoms. He has a medical history of osteoarthritis affecting his knees and hypertension. His regular medications include paracetamol, and perindopril, with celecoxib taken as required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is localised tenderness over the left L4 facet joint. The pain is reproduced with lumbar extension and rotation to the left. Straight leg raise is normal bilaterally with no sensory or motor deficits in the lower limbs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has previously received two left L4 facet joint corticosteroid/anaesthetic injections which provided good pain relief for two to three weeks. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lumbar fusion surgery","Repeat corticosteroid injection","Radiofrequency denervation","Gabapentin therapy","Transcutaneous electrical nerve stimulation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features typical of facet joint arthropathy, including localised back pain that worsens with extension and rotation. The previous positive response to a diagnostic facet joint injection confirms the diagnosis and indicates that the facet joint is the primary pain generator. Facet joint arthropathy also known as facet joint syndrome is considered a common and under diagnosed cause of lower back pain. The lumbar facet joints are innervated by the medial branch of the lumbar spinal nerve at the same level and above, and this can be targeted for therapeutic relief. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiofrequency denervation\u003C/strong\u003E of the medial branch is the most appropriate next step as this patient has demonstrated a positive response to a diagnostic block. This procedure involves thermal ablation of the medial branch nerves that supply the facet joint and can provide longer-lasting pain relief (6-12 months) compared to injections. Even though the patient\u0027s relief from previous injections was relatively short (2-3 weeks), this diagnostic response is still sufficient to proceed with radiofrequency denervation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat corticosteroid injection,\u003C/strong\u003E would likely provide only temporary relief, as demonstrated by the previous injection which only lasted 2-3 weeks. While not contraindicated, it would not offer a longer-term solution that radiofrequency denervation could provide, and 2 effective injections to the region is considered diagnostic of a facet joint condition. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar fusion surgery\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive for facet joint pain alone, particularly given the patient\u0027s age and the availability of less invasive options. Fusion surgery is typically reserved for cases with significant instability or deformity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGabapentin therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the primary treatment for mechanical facet joint pain. It is more appropriate for neuropathic pain conditions, which this patient does not demonstrate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranscutaneous electrical nerve stimulation\u003C/strong\u003E (TENS) has limited evidence in treating facet joint pain and would be unlikely to provide significant benefit given the demonstrated response to facet joint injection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Facet joint pain typically presents in older adults with localised back pain that worsens with extension and rotation.","A positive response to diagnostic facet joint injection supports the diagnosis of facet arthropathy.","Radiofrequency denervation is indicated for patients with proven facet joint pain who have had temporary relief from diagnostic blocks."],"references":["Du R, Xu G, Bai X, Li Z. Facet joint syndrome: pathophysiology, diagnosis, and treatment. Journal of Pain Research. 2022 Jan 1:3689-710. Available online at ; https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.2147/jpr.s389602","Searcy S, Mora J, Meroney M, Jafari A, Henson C, Jenkins K, Mallett B, Shibu V, Ogbemudia B, Vasilopoulos T, Kaye AD. Retrospective Review of the Efficacy of Lumbar Radiofrequency Ablation for Lumbar Facet Arthropathy: The Influence of Gender and Obesity. Pain Physician. 2023;26(6):E695. Available online at ; https://www.painphysicianjournal.com/current/pdf?article=Nzc0OQ%3D%3D\u0026journal=155"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82290"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15560"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82290"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-22T22:36:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-22T22:38:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8251"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99898"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/45"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83e\uddbd","name":"Rehabilitation Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"